Filesystem Hierarchy Standard (FHS):
 
 
The Filesystem Hierarchy Standard (FHS) is a set of guidelines that define the structure and organization of directories and files on Unix-like operating systems, including Linux. It aims to ensure consistency and compatibility between different distributions of Linux, making it easier for software developers, administrators, and users to navigate and understand the file system. Here are the key components of the FHS:


--------------------------------------------------
WHAT IS LINUX DIRECTORY STRUCTURE?
--------------------------------------------------

    Linux follows a hierarchical file system.

    Everything starts from:

        /   (root directory)

    All files and directories are organized
    under this root.


--------------------------------------------------
ROOT DIRECTORY (/)
--------------------------------------------------

    Top-level directory in Linux.

    All other directories exist inside it.

    Example:

        /home
        /etc
        /var

--------------------------------------------------
/home
--------------------------------------------------

    User home directories

    Example:

        /home/ec2-user
        /home/ubuntu

    Stores:
        • User files
        • Personal data


--------------------------------------------------
/root
--------------------------------------------------

    Home directory of root user (admin)

    Not same as /


--------------------------------------------------
/etc
--------------------------------------------------

    Configuration files

    Stores:

        • System configs
        • Service configs

    Example:

        /etc/passwd
        /etc/ssh/sshd_config


--------------------------------------------------
/var
--------------------------------------------------

    Variable data (changes frequently)

    Stores:

        • Logs
        • Cache
        • Application data

    Example:

        /var/log/
        /var/lib/jenkins/
        /var/lib/docker

--------------------------------------------------
/usr
--------------------------------------------------

    User programs and utilities

    Contains:

        • Applications
        • Libraries
        • Documentation

    Example:

        /usr/bin
        /usr/lib


--------------------------------------------------
/bin
--------------------------------------------------

    Essential system commands

    Example:

        ls
        cp
        mv
        cat


--------------------------------------------------
/sbin
--------------------------------------------------

    System/admin commands

    Example:

        reboot
        shutdown
        ifconfig


--------------------------------------------------
/tmp
--------------------------------------------------

    Temporary files

    • Auto-deleted on reboot
    • Used for temporary storage


--------------------------------------------------
/opt
--------------------------------------------------

    Optional software installations

    Example:

        /opt/tomcat
        /opt/custom_apps


--------------------------------------------------
/dev
--------------------------------------------------

    Device files

    Represents hardware devices

    Example:

        /dev/sda
        /dev/null


--------------------------------------------------
/proc
--------------------------------------------------

    Virtual filesystem

    Contains system/process info

    Example:

        /proc/cpuinfo


--------------------------------------------------
/boot
--------------------------------------------------

    Boot loader files

    Required to start system

    Example:

        Kernel files


--------------------------------------------------
/mnt and /media
--------------------------------------------------

    Used to mount external storage

    Example:

        USB drives
        EBS volumes


--------------------------------------------------
IMPORTANT DEVOPS DIRECTORIES
--------------------------------------------------

    /var/log
        Logs for debugging

    /etc
        Configurations

    /var/lib
        Application data (Jenkins, Docker)

    /home
        User scripts and files


--------------------------------------------------
SIMPLE STRUCTURE VIEW
--------------------------------------------------

        /
        ├── home
        ├── root
        ├── etc
        ├── var
        ├── usr
        ├── bin
        ├── sbin
        ├── tmp
        ├── opt
        ├── dev
        ├── proc
        ├── boot


--------------------------------------------------
REAL DEVOPS USE CASE
--------------------------------------------------

    • Check logs → /var/log
    • Modify configs → /etc
    • Install apps → /opt
    • Store user data → /home
    • Debug system → /proc

